directions.Direction: With your pot over medium low heat, add your milk and heavy cream & stir
Continue stirring throughout the process so you don’t burn the milk/cream & also so you don’t get a film on the top of your liquid
Once your mixture starts steaming, check your temperature. At 150 degrees, I usually leave my thermometer in my mixture for ease of temperature tracking
Continue stirring, you'll be stirring for a good 30 mins!
When your thermometer reaches 190-200 degrees Fahrenheit, turn your heat off and immediately add your salt and vinegar
Give your mixture one last stir and let sit for 10 minutes
After 10 minutes, you can see that the cheese will curdle and will separate from the liquid, making a whey
Sit your mesh strainer on top of a large bowl, with your cheese cloth over the strainer
Using a slotted spoon, spoon your ricotta over the cheese cloth
Option to squeeze cheesecloth to drain the excess liquid out of your ricotta.
For more moist ricotta, let sit/drain for 1 hour in the fridge
For drier ricotta, to use in filled pasta or lasagna, let sit/drain for 3 or more hours in the fridge until it is at the consistency you want!
Store in an airtight container for 3-5 days, and enjoy!
Helpful tips:
A thick, heavy-bottomed pot, like a dutch oven is best so you don't burn your ricotta
Use heavy cream NOT heavy whipping cream - you need the higher fat content for your ricotta to set

The liquid that separates from the Ricotta is called whey. You actually can save this liquid and use it in other recipes instead of throwing it out! It's similar to adding chicken stock instead of water to recipes for more taste.
If your ricotta does not separate from the liquid, you may not have enough fat in your cream or temperature may be too low

directions.Direction: Heat olive oil in a large heavy bottom pot, like a dutch oven
Add 3 cloves of minced garlic & let simmer until just golden & fragrant

While sauce simmers on low, start browning meat
First the ribs, which take the longest to cook-

Brown on all sides until each side is golden, about 5 mins on each side

Once all meatballs are browned, add that delicious oil & drippings to your sauce & mix fully into sauce
Add dash of salt & pepper and simmer all together on low for 5-6 hours until meat is cooked through

Gently stir throughout the simmer, every 20 mins or so making sure your sauce is not not burning at the bottom of your pot (this is why you want a heavy bottom pot so the flame isn’t too close to the sauce)
After about 3 hours of simmering, if your sauce has thinned down, option to add tomato paste to thicken up, and for added flavor

directions.Direction: To Make the Pasta:
Make a well with your flour on a clean, flat surface or in a bowl
Add eggs & salt into your well & scramble eggs gently within the well
Pull flour into your well a little at a time until it resembles a batter [move to a flat surface if using a bowl]
Once it starts forming into a ball, start hand kneading (TIP: A Dough scraper can be very helpful with initial kneading)
Kneading motion is folding top over itself, pressing down with heel of hand & then rotating at 90 degrees, repeating this pattern throughout the process
